Silicon is the eighth most abundant element in the universe by mass, and the second most abundant element by mass in the Earth's crust, making up 25.9% of the earth's crust by mass. Silicon does not occur as a pure free element in nature but forms silicon dioxide and silicates. Silicates are compounds of silicon and oxygen, with silicon always having four bonds, and oxygen having three. Silicon is the second most abundant element in Earth's crust, after oxygen. Moscow treaty Moscow treaty The Moscow treaty of 1949, officially titled the Treaty on Friendship, Co-operation and Mutual Assistance, was a treaty of friendship, co-operation and mutual assistance signed between the Soviet Union and the People's Republic of China on 30 August 1949. The treaty was concluded for a period of 5 years and stipulated that the two countries would "respect each other's sovereignty, equality, territorial integrity and inviolability".
